context: The English term comics derives from the humorous (or "comic") work which predominated in early American <a0_0><b5_0>newspaper comic strips<b5_0/><a0_0/>; usage of the term has become standard for <a1_0><b6_0>non-humorous<b6_0/><a1_0/> works as well. The term "comic book" has a similarly confusing history: they are most often not humorous; nor are they regular books, but rather <a2_0><b7_0>periodicals<b7_0/><a2_0/>. It is common in English to refer to the comics of different cultures by the terms used in their original languages, such as <a3_0><b8_0>manga<b8_0/><a3_0/> for Japanese comics, or <a4_0><b9_0>bandes dessinées<b9_0/><a4_0/> for French-language Franco-Belgian comics.
